              'correction, and painful growth. Yet unlike punishment that is '
              'motivated by anger, God\'s discipline flows from His perfect love. He '
              'corrects His children because He desires their maturity, not their '
              'destruction. '
              '\n'
              'Many believers misunderstand difficult seasons, assuming God has '
              'abandoned them or is angry with them. Yet Scripture reveals that '
              'loving fathers discipline the children they cherish. As Solomon writes '
              'in Book of Proverbs 3:11–12, the Lord disciplines those He loves, just '
              'as a father delights in his child. God\'s correction is evidence of '
              'relationship, not rejection. '
              '\n'
              'The hand that disciplines you is the same hand that lovingly holds '
              'and guides you. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'Growth Often Comes Through Discomfort',
          body:
              'Hebrews honestly acknowledges that discipline is painful rather than '
              'pleasant. Spiritual growth rarely happens while remaining comfortable. '
              'God often allows situations that stretch our faith, expose our '
              'weaknesses, and challenge our dependence upon Him because these are '
              'the moments when transformation takes place. '
              '\n'
              'Human nature prefers immediate comfort, but God is committed to '
              'eternal growth. Just as a gardener prunes healthy branches to produce '
              'more fruit, God lovingly removes attitudes, habits, and desires that '
              'hinder spiritual maturity. As Jesus teaches in Gospel of John 15:2, '
              'every fruitful branch is pruned so that it may bear even more fruit. '
              '\n'
              'Temporary discomfort often prepares us for lasting spiritual '
              'strength. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'God\'s Discipline Trains the Heart',
          body:
              'The writer explains that discipline produces fruit in those who are '
              '"trained by it." Training requires humility, teachability, and '
              'perseverance. God\'s correction is most effective when believers '
              'respond with willing hearts instead of resentment or resistance. Every '
              'challenge becomes an opportunity to learn the Father\'s wisdom. '
              '\n'
              'The enemy wants believers to become bitter during seasons of '
              'correction, but God invites them to become better. Instead of asking, '
              '"Why is this happening to me?" faith begins asking, "Lord, what are '
              'You teaching me?" As James encourages in Epistle of James 1:2–4, the '
              'testing of faith develops perseverance and spiritual maturity. '
              '\n'
              'A teachable heart turns painful experiences into lifelong wisdom. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'Righteousness Is the Fruit of a Transformed Life',
          body:
              'God\'s discipline ultimately produces "the peaceable fruit of '
              'righteousness." His goal is not simply to correct behavior but to '
              'transform character. Righteousness is the visible evidence of a heart '
              'that is becoming more like Christ. Over time, obedience becomes more '
              'natural because the Holy Spirit is continually shaping the believer '
              'from within. '
              '\n'
              'Many people desire the fruit of righteousness without embracing the '
              'process that produces it. Yet every season of discipline is preparing '
              'believers for greater holiness, deeper peace, and stronger faith. As '
              'Paul writes in Epistle to the Romans 8:29, God is conforming His '
              'children into the image of His Son. Every act of discipline serves '
              'this glorious purpose. '
              '\n'
              'God is more concerned with who you are becoming than with where you '
              'are today. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'The Harvest Is Greater Than the Pain',
          body:
              'Hebrews emphasizes the word "afterward." During discipline, it is '
              'often difficult to see the purpose behind the pain. But with time, '
              'believers begin to recognize how God used those very seasons to '
              'strengthen faith, deepen character, and prepare them for greater '
              'usefulness. The harvest always comes after the process. '
              '\n'
              'Looking back, many believers can identify seasons they once resisted '
              'but now thank God for because those experiences drew them closer to '
              'Him. As Paul declares in Epistle to the Romans 5:3–5, tribulation '
              'produces perseverance, character, and hope. God\'s process is never '
              'wasted because His purpose is always good. '
              '\n'
              'The pain of God\'s discipline is temporary, but the fruit it produces '
              'lasts for eternity. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'God\'s discipline is never meant to break you—it is meant to shape '
          'you. The Father\'s correction is not evidence of His rejection, but '
          'proof of His love and commitment to your spiritual growth. ---',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Is there a difficult season that God may be using to shape my '
        'character?',
        'Am I resisting God\'s correction or allowing it to train my heart?',
        'What fruit of righteousness is God seeking to develop in my life '
        'through this season?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord, '
          '\n'
          'Thank You for loving me enough to discipline me when I need '
          'correction. Help me remember that Your discipline is never motivated '
          'by anger but by Your desire to make me more like Jesus Christ. '
          '\n'
          'Forgive me for the times I have resisted Your work or complained '
          'about difficult seasons without seeking to understand Your purpose. '
          'Give me a humble and teachable heart that is willing to learn '
          'everything You desire to teach me. '
          '\n'
          'Strengthen me to endure the process of growth with faith and '
          'patience. Produce within me the peaceable fruit of righteousness, and '
          'let my life increasingly reflect the character of Christ. Help me '
          'trust that every moment of discipline is preparing me for something '
          'greater. '
          '\n'
          'May I never despise Your loving correction, but receive it with '
          'gratitude, knowing that the Father who disciplines me is also the '
          'Father who is preparing me for eternal glory. '
          '\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 14),
    ),

    // ── 75. LIVING ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'living_the_word',
      theme: 'Living',
      title: 'Living the Word, Not Just Hearing It',
      scripture:
          'But be doers of the word, and not hearers only, deceiving yourselves.',
      scriptureReference: 'James 1:22',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'God\'s Word Was Given to Transform Lives',
          body:
              'James challenges believers to move beyond simply hearing God\'s Word. '
              'Listening to Scripture, attending church, or studying the Bible are '
              'valuable, but they are only the beginning. God\'s ultimate purpose is '
              'not merely to fill our minds with knowledge but to transform our '
              'hearts and shape our daily lives. '
              '\n'
              'Many believers know numerous Bible verses but struggle to apply them '
              'in everyday situations. Spiritual maturity is not measured by how much '
              'Scripture we can quote but by how faithfully we live it. As Jesus '
              'declared in Gospel of John 13:17, "If you know these things, blessed '
              'are you if you do them." Knowledge without obedience produces little '
              'spiritual fruit. '
              '\n'
              'God\'s Word reaches its full purpose when it changes the way we live. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'Hearing Without Obeying Leads to Self-Deception',
          body:
              'James gives a strong warning against being "hearers only." It is '
              'possible to believe we are spiritually healthy simply because we '
              'regularly hear God\'s Word, while our lives remain unchanged. This '
              'false confidence is dangerous because it creates the illusion of '
              'spiritual growth without genuine transformation. '
              '\n'
              'The enemy is content when believers admire God\'s truth without '
              'applying it. He knows that an unapplied Bible has little impact on '
              'daily living. Jesus illustrated this truth in Gospel of Matthew '
              '7:24–27 by comparing those who hear and obey His words to a wise man '
              'who built his house upon the rock. Stability comes through obedience, '
              'not merely through information. '
              '\n'
              'True spirituality is revealed by obedience, not simply by knowledge. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'Obedience Demonstrates Genuine Faith',
          body:
              'Every act of obedience is an expression of trust in God. When '
              'believers obey His Word, they declare that God\'s wisdom is greater '
              'than their own understanding. Obedience often requires faith because '
              'it calls us to follow God\'s direction even when it is difficult or '
              'unpopular. '
              '\n'
              'The world encourages people to follow their feelings, but God\'s Word '
              'calls believers to follow His truth. There will be moments when '
              'obedience requires sacrifice, patience, forgiveness, or courage. Yet '
              'every step of obedience draws believers closer to God\'s purposes. As '
              'Samuel declared in Book of First Samuel 15:22, obedience is better '
              'than sacrifice because it reflects a heart fully surrendered to God. '
              '\n'
              'Faith becomes visible when it is expressed through obedience. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'God\'s Word Produces Lasting Transformation',
          body:
              'When believers consistently obey God\'s Word, their lives gradually '
              'begin to reflect the character of Christ. Old habits lose their power, '
              'attitudes change, relationships improve, and spiritual fruit begins to '
              'grow. Transformation is often gradual, but it is always evident in a '
              'life surrendered to God. '
              '\n'
              'Many people seek quick spiritual growth while avoiding the daily '
              'discipline of obeying God\'s truth. Yet lasting change happens one act '
              'of obedience at a time. As Paul teaches in Epistle to the Romans 12:2, '
              'believers are transformed through the renewing of their minds. Every '
              'decision to obey allows God\'s Word to shape the heart more deeply. '
              '\n'
              'The Bible is not merely a book to be studied—it is a life to be '
              'lived. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Obedience Brings God\'s Blessing',
          body:
              'James later explains that the person who continues in God\'s Word and '
              'practices it will be blessed in what they do. God\'s blessings are not '
              'earned through obedience, but obedience positions believers to '
              'experience the joy, peace, wisdom, and fruitfulness that flow from '
              'walking in His will. '
              '\n'
              'Obedience does not guarantee an easy life, but it guarantees the '
              'satisfaction of walking closely with God. Even when the path is '
              'difficult, there is peace in knowing that we are living according to '
              'His purpose. As David writes in Book of Psalms 119:105, God\'s Word is '
              'a lamp to our feet and a light to our path. Those who follow His '
              'guidance never walk alone. '
              '\n'
              'The greatest blessing is not found in merely knowing God\'s Word, but '
              'in allowing His Word to shape every part of our lives. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'God did not give you His Word simply to increase your knowledge—He '
          'gave it to transform your life. Every truth you obey becomes another '
          'step toward becoming more like Christ. ---',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Am I merely hearing God\'s Word, or am I intentionally living it each '
        'day?',
        'Is there an area of my life where I know God\'s will but have delayed '
        'obedience?',
        'What practical step of obedience is God asking me to take today?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord, '
          '\n'
          'Thank You for the gift of Your living and powerful Word. Thank You '
          'that You speak to my heart through the Scriptures and reveal Your will '
          'for my life. Forgive me for the times I have listened to Your truth '
          'without allowing it to transform my actions. '
          '\n'
          'Give me a humble and obedient heart. Help me not to settle for '
          'knowing Your Word, but to faithfully live it in my thoughts, words, '
          'and actions. Strengthen me to obey You even when it is difficult, '
          'trusting that Your ways are always good and lead to life. '
          '\n'
          'Renew my mind each day through Your truth. Let Your Word shape my '
          'character, guide my decisions, and produce the fruit of righteousness '
          'in my life. May others see Christ reflected in the way I live, love, '
          'and serve. '
          '\n'
          'May I be more than a hearer of Your Word—may I become a faithful doer '
          'who brings glory to Your name through a life of joyful obedience. '
          '\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 15),
    ),

    // ── 76. ABIDING ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'abiding_in_christ',
      theme: 'Abiding',
      title: 'Abiding in Christ, Living in Answered Prayer',
      scripture:
          'If you abide in Me, and My words abide in you, you will ask what you '
          'desire, and it shall be done for you.',
      scriptureReference: 'John 15:7',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'Abiding in Christ Is the Foundation of the Christian Life',
          body:
              'Jesus begins with an invitation rather than a command: "If you abide '
              'in Me." To abide means to remain, dwell, and continue in a close '
              'relationship with Him. Christianity is not simply following religious '
              'principles or attending church services; it is living every day in '
              'intimate fellowship with Jesus. Just as a branch draws life from the '
              'vine, believers receive spiritual life, strength, and fruitfulness by '
              'remaining connected to Christ. '
              '\n'
              'Many believers become spiritually weary because they focus more on '
              'working for Christ than walking with Christ. Activity without intimacy '
              'eventually leads to exhaustion. Jesus makes it clear in Gospel of John '
              '15:5 that apart from Him we can do nothing. Lasting spiritual fruit is '
              'not produced through human effort but through continual dependence '
              'upon Him. '
              '\n'
              'The strength of your Christian life is determined by the depth of '
              'your relationship with Christ. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'God\'s Word Must Find a Home in Your Heart',
          body:
              'Jesus continues by saying, "and My words abide in you." It is not '
              'enough for believers to occasionally read God\'s Word; His truth must '
              'live within them, shaping their thoughts, attitudes, decisions, and '
              'desires. A heart filled with God\'s Word becomes sensitive to His voice '
              'and aligned with His will. '
              '\n'
              'In a world filled with competing voices, God\'s Word provides wisdom, '
              'stability, and direction. It renews the mind and guards the heart '
              'against deception. As David declares in Book of Psalms 119:11, hiding '
              'God\'s Word in the heart helps believers resist sin. The more Scripture '
              'dwells within us, the more our lives begin to reflect the character of '
              'Christ. '
              '\n'
              'A heart filled with God\'s Word becomes fertile ground for spiritual '
              'growth. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'Abiding Changes the Way We Pray',
          body:
              'Jesus promises that those who abide in Him may ask what they desire, '
              'and it will be done. This is not a promise that God grants every '
              'selfish request. Rather, abiding transforms the believer\'s desires '
              'until they increasingly reflect God\'s own heart. As our relationship '
              'with Christ deepens, our prayers become aligned with His purposes. '
              '\n'
              'Many unanswered prayers result not from God\'s unwillingness but from '
              'desires that have not yet been shaped by His will. As John writes in '
              'First Epistle of John 5:14, confidence in prayer comes when we ask '
              'according to God\'s will. The closer we walk with Christ, the more our '
              'prayers reflect His wisdom, compassion, and eternal purposes. '
              '\n'
              'The secret to powerful prayer is not learning better words—it is '
              'cultivating a deeper relationship with Jesus. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'A Fruitful Life Flows from Intimacy with Christ',
          body:
              'The purpose of abiding is not merely answered prayer but a fruitful '
              'life. Fruit grows naturally on a healthy branch that remains connected '
              'to the vine. In the same way, love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, '
              'faithfulness, and every other spiritual fruit develop naturally in the '
              'life that remains close to Christ. '
              '\n'
              'Many believers become discouraged because they focus on producing '
              'fruit through self-effort. Yet fruit is the result of abiding, not '
              'striving. As Paul teaches in Epistle to the Galatians 5:22–23, the '
              'fruit of the Spirit is produced by the Holy Spirit working within us. '
              'The closer we remain to Jesus, the more His character becomes visible '
              'in our lives. '
              '\n'
              'Spiritual fruit is the evidence of a life continually connected to '
              'the true Vine. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Abiding Is a Daily Choice',
          body:
              'Remaining in Christ is not a one-time decision but a daily '
              'commitment. Every day believers choose to seek His presence through '
              'prayer, meditate on His Word, obey His voice, and trust His guidance. '
              'Abiding requires intentional dependence because the distractions of '
              'the world constantly compete for our attention. '
              '\n'
              'There will always be pressures that tempt believers to drift from '
              'intimacy with Christ. Yet His invitation remains the same: remain in '
              'Me. As the writer of Epistle to the Hebrews 12:2 encourages, believers '
              'are to fix their eyes on Jesus, the author and finisher of their '
              'faith. A life centered on Christ is strengthened, sustained, and '
              'filled with lasting peace. '
              '\n'
              'Those who remain close to Christ will discover that He is everything '
              'their souls truly need. '
              '\n'
              '---',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'The power of the Christian life is not found in striving—it is found '
          'in abiding. When you remain in Christ, His Word shapes your heart, '
          'your prayers align with His will, and your life begins to bear fruit '
          'that will last for eternity. ---',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Am I spending more time working for Christ than abiding with Him?',
        'Is God\'s Word shaping my thoughts and desires each day?',
        'Do my prayers reflect my own will, or are they becoming aligned with '
        'God\'s heart?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord, '
          '\n'
          'Thank You for inviting me into a close and personal relationship with '
          'You. Thank You that I do not have to live the Christian life in my own '
          'strength, but that You have called me to remain in You as a branch '
          'remains connected to the vine. '
          '\n'
          'Teach me to abide in Your presence every day. Let Your Word dwell '
          'richly in my heart, shaping my thoughts, renewing my mind, and guiding '
          'my decisions. Remove every distraction that pulls me away from '
          'intimate fellowship with You. '
          '\n'
          'Transform my desires until they reflect Your heart. Help me pray with '
          'faith, confidence, and submission to Your perfect will. Produce in me '
          'the fruit of the Holy Spirit so that my life will bring glory to You '
          'and become a blessing to others. '
          '\n'
          'May I remain firmly rooted in You, drawing my strength, wisdom, '
          'peace, and joy from Your unfailing presence, and may my life bear '
          'fruit that will remain for Your glory. '
          '\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 16),
    ),


    // ── 77. GODS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'gods_deliverance_through',
      theme: 'Gods',
      title: 'God\'s Deliverance Through Every Trial',
      scripture:
          'Many are the afflictions of the righteous, but the Lord delivers him\n'
          'out of them all.',
      scriptureReference: 'Psalms 34:19',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'Righteousness Does Not Eliminate Trials',
          body:
              'David begins with an honest truth: "Many are the afflictions of the\n'
              'righteous." Following God does not guarantee a life free from pain,\n'
              'disappointment, persecution, or hardship. In fact, those who desire to\n'
              'live faithfully often encounter challenges because they are walking\n'
              'against the current of a fallen world.\n'
              'Many believers become discouraged when difficulties arise, wondering\n'
              'if God has abandoned them or if they have somehow failed. Yet\n'
              'Scripture consistently shows that God\'s faithful servants endured many\n'
              'trials. Joseph was imprisoned, Daniel faced the lions\' den, Paul\n'
              'suffered persecution, and even Jesus endured suffering. As Paul writes\n'
              'in Second Epistle to Timothy 3:12, those who desire to live godly\n'
              'lives in Christ Jesus will face opposition.\n'
              'The presence of trials is not evidence of God\'s absence—it is often\n'
              'part of the journey of faith.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'God\'s Presence Is Greater Than Every Affliction',
          body:
              'Although afflictions are many, David immediately shifts the focus to\n'
              'God. He does not magnify the problems; he magnifies the Deliverer. The\n'
              'believer\'s confidence is not found in the size of the trial but in the\n'
              'greatness of the God who walks with them through it.\n'
              'The enemy seeks to make difficulties appear larger than God\'s\n'
              'promises. Fear grows when our eyes remain fixed on circumstances.\n'
              'Faith grows when our eyes remain fixed on the Lord. As God declared\n'
              'through Book of Isaiah 41:10, "Fear not, for I am with you." His\n'
              'presence gives strength when our own strength is exhausted.\n'
              'Your afflictions may be many, but God\'s faithfulness is greater than\n'
              'every one of them.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'Deliverance Comes in God\'s Perfect Way',
          body:
              'David confidently declares that "the Lord delivers him out of them\n'
              'all." God\'s deliverance is certain, but it does not always look the\n'
              'way we expect. Sometimes He delivers us from trouble by removing it.\n'
              'At other times, He delivers us through trouble by giving us the\n'
              'strength, wisdom, and grace to endure until His purpose is fulfilled.\n'
              'Throughout Scripture, God\'s deliverance took many forms. He brought\n'
              'Israel through the Red Sea, protected Daniel in the lions\' den, and\n'
              'strengthened Paul while he remained in prison. As Paul testified in\n'
              'Second Epistle to Timothy 4:18, the Lord rescued him and preserved him\n'
              'for His heavenly kingdom. God\'s methods may vary, but His faithfulness\n'
              'never changes.\n'
              'God\'s deliverance is not limited by your circumstances because His\n'
              'power is greater than every trial.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'Trials Produce Deeper Trust',
          body:
              'Afflictions often become the place where faith matures most deeply.\n'
              'During seasons of comfort, believers may depend upon their own\n'
              'abilities, but trials teach them to lean completely upon God. What\n'
              'begins as pain often becomes the pathway to greater intimacy with Him.\n'
              '\n'
              'Many of the strongest testimonies are born from the darkest valleys.\n'
              'David learned to trust God while fleeing from enemies, and Paul\n'
              'discovered God\'s sufficient grace through weakness. As James teaches\n'
              'in Epistle of James 1:2–4, the testing of faith produces perseverance\n'
              'and spiritual maturity. God never wastes the pain of His children.\n'
              'The valley often becomes the classroom where believers learn to trust\n'
              'God more completely.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Hope Rests in God\'s Unfailing Faithfulness',
          body:
              'Psalm 34:19 ends with hope. The believer\'s story does not end with\n'
              'affliction because God always has the final word. Every hardship is\n'
              'temporary, but God\'s faithfulness is eternal. Even when answers seem\n'
              'delayed, believers can rest in the assurance that God is working for\n'
              'their good and His glory.\n'
              'This hope allows believers to persevere with confidence. As Paul\n'
              'declares in Epistle to the Romans 8:28, God works all things together\n'
              'for the good of those who love Him and are called according to His\n'
              'purpose. No trial is beyond His control, and no sorrow is beyond His\n'
              'comfort.\n'
              'Those who trust God\'s faithfulness discover that every affliction has\n'
              'an expiration date, but His promises endure forever.\n'
              '---',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'Your trials may be numerous, your burdens may feel heavy, and your\n'
          'journey may be difficult—but none of your afflictions are greater than\n'
          'the God who promises to deliver you. God never abandons His children\n'
          'in the fire; He walks with them until they reach the other side. ---',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Am I allowing my trials to become greater than my view of God?',
        'How has God delivered me through previous seasons of hardship?',
        'What current affliction is God inviting me to trust Him with today?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for reminding me that although the righteous face many\n'
          'afflictions, You remain the faithful Deliverer. Thank You that You\n'
          'never promise a life without trials, but You do promise Your constant\n'
          'presence and unfailing help.\n'
          'Forgive me for the times I have allowed fear and discouragement to\n'
          'overshadow my faith. Help me keep my eyes fixed on You instead of my\n'
          'circumstances. Strengthen me to trust Your wisdom when I cannot\n'
          'understand Your ways and to believe that Your deliverance will come at\n'
          'the perfect time.\n'
          'Use every trial to deepen my faith, refine my character, and draw me\n'
          'closer to You. Let every hardship become an opportunity to experience\n'
          'Your grace and discover Your faithfulness in a greater way.\n'
          'May I walk through every season with confidence, knowing that no\n'
          'affliction is greater than my God, and that the One who has delivered\n'
          'me before will never fail to deliver me again.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 17),
    ),

    // ── 78. LIVING ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'living_under_the',
      theme: 'Living',
      title: 'Living Under the Watchful Eyes of God',
      scripture:
          'For the eyes of the Lord are on the righteous, and His ears are open\n'
          'to their prayers; but the face of the Lord is against those who do\n'
          'evil.',
      scriptureReference: '1 Peter 3:12',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'God Watches Over His Children with Loving Care',
          body:
              'Peter reminds believers that "the eyes of the Lord are on the\n'
              'righteous." This is not the watchful gaze of a distant observer but\n'
              'the loving attention of a caring Father. God continually watches over\n'
              'His people, fully aware of every joy, every sorrow, every struggle,\n'
              'and every victory. Nothing escapes His notice, and nothing in our\n'
              'lives is hidden from Him.\n'
              'Many believers feel unnoticed during seasons of hardship or\n'
              'loneliness. They wonder if God sees their tears, hears their silent\n'
              'cries, or understands their pain. Yet Scripture assures us that God\'s\n'
              'attention never leaves His children. As David declares in Book of\n'
              'Psalms 121:3–4, the Keeper of Israel neither slumbers nor sleeps. His\n'
              'loving eyes remain fixed upon His people day and night.\n'
              'You are never forgotten because you are always within the Father\'s\n'
              'loving sight.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'God Hears Every Sincere Prayer',
          body:
              'Peter also declares that God\'s ears are open to the prayers of the\n'
              'righteous. Prayer is not a ritual performed before an unwilling God—it\n'
              'is a conversation with a Father who delights in hearing His children.\n'
              'Every sincere prayer, whether spoken with confidence or whispered\n'
              'through tears, reaches His attentive heart.\n'
              'There are moments when answers seem delayed, causing believers to\n'
              'question whether God is listening. Yet silence should never be\n'
              'mistaken for indifference. God\'s timing is always perfect, and His\n'
              'wisdom exceeds our understanding. As Jesus taught in Gospel of Matthew\n'
              '7:7–11, the Heavenly Father gladly gives good gifts to those who ask\n'
              'Him. Every prayer is heard, even when the answer unfolds differently\n'
              'than expected.\n'
              'Heaven\'s ears are always open to hearts that sincerely seek God.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'Righteous Living Brings Fellowship with God',
          body:
              'Peter describes those whom God watches over as "the righteous." This\n'
              'righteousness is not earned through human perfection but received\n'
              'through faith in Jesus Christ. However, those who belong to Christ are\n'
              'also called to pursue lives that reflect His holiness. Obedience\n'
              'strengthens fellowship with God and allows believers to enjoy the\n'
              'peace that comes from walking in His will.\n'
              'The enemy often seeks to separate believers from God through\n'
              'compromise, temptation, and disobedience. Yet God\'s invitation is\n'
              'always one of restoration and close fellowship. As John writes in\n'
              'First Epistle of John 1:9, when believers confess their sins, God is\n'
              'faithful to forgive and cleanse them. A life surrendered to God enjoys\n'
              'the blessing of continual communion with Him.\n'
              'God delights in drawing near to those whose hearts are devoted to\n'
              'Him.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'God Is Holy and Opposes Evil',
          body:
              'Peter also reminds us that "the face of the Lord is against those who\n'
              'do evil." This statement reveals God\'s perfect holiness and justice.\n'
              'Because God is perfectly righteous, He cannot approve of sin or ignore\n'
              'evil. His opposition to wickedness is not inconsistent with His\n'
              'love—it is an expression of His holy character.\n'
              'This truth should inspire believers to pursue holiness with reverence\n'
              'and humility. Rather than treating sin lightly, we are called to turn\n'
              'away from anything that grieves God\'s heart. As Paul writes in Epistle\n'
              'to the Ephesians 5:8–10, believers are to walk as children of light,\n'
              'seeking what is pleasing to the Lord. God\'s holiness calls His people\n'
              'to live differently from the world around them.\n'
              'The God who lovingly watches over His children also lovingly calls\n'
              'them to holy living.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Live Each Day in the Confidence of God\'s Presence',
          body:
              'Knowing that God\'s eyes are upon us and His ears are open to our\n'
              'prayers changes the way we live. We no longer walk through life\n'
              'feeling abandoned or forgotten. Whether we experience joy or sorrow,\n'
              'success or difficulty, we can rest in the assurance that God is near\n'
              'and actively involved in every detail of our lives.\n'
              'This confidence gives believers courage to face uncertainty with\n'
              'peace. They know that every prayer is heard, every tear is seen, and\n'
              'every act of faithfulness is remembered. As the writer of Epistle to\n'
              'the Hebrews 13:5–6 reminds us, God has promised never to leave or\n'
              'forsake His people. His constant presence becomes the believer\'s\n'
              'greatest source of strength.\n'
              'Those who live under God\'s watchful care can face every season\n'
              'without fear.\n'
              '---',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'God\'s eyes are always upon you. His ears are always open to your\n'
          'prayers. His heart is always faithful to His promises. You never face\n'
          'a single moment of life outside the loving care of your Heavenly\n'
          'Father. ---',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Do I truly believe that God sees every detail of my life?',
        'Am I bringing my concerns to God with confidence, knowing that He\n'
        'hears my prayers?',
        'Does my daily life reflect a desire to walk in holiness before the\n'
        'God who watches over me?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for Your constant love and faithful care. Thank You that\n'
          'Your eyes are always upon me and that Your ears are always open to my\n'
          'prayers. I find great comfort in knowing that I never walk alone and\n'
          'that nothing in my life escapes Your attention.\n'
          'Forgive me for the times I have doubted Your presence or questioned\n'
          'whether You heard my prayers. Strengthen my faith to trust that You\n'
          'are always working, even when I cannot yet see the answer. Help me\n'
          'live each day with confidence in Your loving care.\n'
          'Teach me to pursue righteousness and to turn away from anything that\n'
          'grieves Your heart. Let my life reflect Your holiness, and may my\n'
          'relationship with You grow deeper each day. Help me rest in the\n'
          'assurance that I am held securely in Your hands.\n'
          'May I walk each day with peace, courage, and unwavering trust,\n'
          'knowing that the God who watches over me will never fail, never\n'
          'forget, and never forsake me.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 18),
    ),

    // ── 79. MOVING ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'moving_forward_without',
      theme: 'Moving',
      title: 'Moving Forward Without Looking Back',
      scripture:
          'But Jesus said to him, ‘No one, having put his hand to the plow, and\n'
          'looking back, is fit for the kingdom of God.',
      scriptureReference: 'Luke 9:62',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'Following Christ Requires Total Commitment',
          body:
              'Jesus spoke these words to someone who desired to follow Him but\n'
              'wanted to delay his commitment. Using the illustration of a farmer\n'
              'plowing a field, Jesus revealed that discipleship requires unwavering\n'
              'focus. A farmer who constantly looks behind cannot plow a straight\n'
              'path. Likewise, believers cannot faithfully follow Christ while\n'
              'continually longing for the life they have left behind.\n'
              'Many people desire the blessings of God\'s kingdom while remaining\n'
              'attached to old habits, worldly priorities, or personal ambitions. Yet\n'
              'Jesus calls His followers to wholehearted devotion. As He declares in\n'
              'Gospel of Matthew 6:24, no one can serve two masters. A divided heart\n'
              'will always struggle to walk faithfully with God.\n'
              'The Christian life begins when Christ becomes your highest priority.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'Looking Back Can Hinder Spiritual Progress',
          body:
              'Jesus was not condemning healthy memories or gratitude for the past.\n'
              'He was warning against a heart that continually longs for what God has\n'
              'called us to leave behind. Looking back with regret, unhealthy\n'
              'attachment, or divided loyalty prevents believers from fully embracing\n'
              'God\'s present calling.\n'
              'The Israelites repeatedly looked back to Egypt, forgetting the\n'
              'bondage they had been delivered from. Their longing for the past kept\n'
              'them from trusting God for the future. As Paul declares in Epistle to\n'
              'the Philippians 3:13–14, believers are called to forget what lies\n'
              'behind and press toward the prize of God\'s upward calling. Spiritual\n'
              'growth requires forward movement.\n'
              'You cannot fully embrace God\'s future while continually clinging to\n'
              'yesterday.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'The Kingdom Calls for Undivided Hearts',
          body:
              'Jesus says that one who looks back is "not fit for the kingdom of\n'
              'God." He is not speaking of perfection but of wholehearted readiness.\n'
              'God desires disciples whose hearts are fully devoted to Him. The\n'
              'kingdom advances through people who are willing to trust God\n'
              'completely, even when the path ahead is uncertain.\n'
              'The enemy often uses distractions, regrets, fear, and divided\n'
              'affections to weaken commitment. He knows that a distracted believer\n'
              'becomes less effective in God\'s service. Yet God continually calls His\n'
              'people to fix their hearts upon Him. As the writer of Epistle to the\n'
              'Hebrews 12:1–2 encourages, believers are to lay aside every weight and\n'
              'keep their eyes fixed on Jesus.\n'
              'A focused heart becomes a fruitful heart in God\'s kingdom.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'God\'s Future Is Greater Than Your Past',
          body:
              'One of Satan\'s greatest strategies is to keep believers imprisoned by\n'
              'past failures, regrets, disappointments, or even past successes. But\n'
              'God is always calling His children forward. His grace not only\n'
              'forgives the past but also prepares them for new purposes and greater\n'
              'opportunities.\n'
              'Throughout Scripture, God called people to leave the familiar behind.\n'
              'Abraham left his homeland. Elisha left his oxen. The disciples left\n'
              'their fishing nets. Each discovered that what God had prepared was far\n'
              'greater than what they left behind. As God declares in Book of Isaiah\n'
              '43:18–19, His people should not dwell on former things because He is\n'
              'doing something new.\n'
              'God never asks you to leave something behind without preparing\n'
              'something better ahead.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Keep Your Eyes Fixed on Christ',
          body:
              'The Christian journey is not sustained by occasional moments of\n'
              'commitment but by daily faithfulness. Every day believers must choose\n'
              'to keep their eyes upon Jesus rather than becoming distracted by fear,\n'
              'regret, or worldly desires. The closer we walk with Him, the clearer\n'
              'our purpose becomes.\n'
              'Life will always present opportunities to become discouraged or\n'
              'distracted, but Christ remains the perfect example of steadfast\n'
              'obedience. As Paul encourages in Epistle to the Colossians 3:1–2,\n'
              'believers should set their minds on things above, not on earthly\n'
              'things. A heart fixed on Christ will continue moving forward\n'
              'regardless of what lies behind.\n'
              'Those who keep their eyes on Jesus will never lose sight of their\n'
              'eternal destination.\n'
              '---',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'God cannot lead you into your future if your heart is continually\n'
          'living in the past. The kingdom belongs to those who keep their hands\n'
          'on the plow, their eyes on Christ, and their hearts fully committed to\n'
          'His calling. ---',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Is there anything from my past that is preventing me from fully\n'
        'following Christ?',
        'Have I allowed fear, regret, or comfort to distract me from God\'s\n'
        'calling?',
        'What step of faith is Jesus asking me to take without looking back?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for calling me to follow You wholeheartedly. Thank You for\n'
          'Your grace that forgives my past and Your faithfulness that leads me\n'
          'into the future You have prepared for me.\n'
          'Forgive me for the times I have looked back with regret, fear, or\n'
          'divided loyalty. Help me release everything You have asked me to leave\n'
          'behind and trust that Your plans are always better than my own. Give\n'
          'me the courage to move forward without hesitation.\n'
          'Keep my heart fully devoted to You. Remove every distraction that\n'
          'weakens my commitment, and teach me to fix my eyes on Jesus each day.\n'
          'Strengthen me to remain faithful through every season, knowing that\n'
          'Your calling is worth every sacrifice.\n'
          'May my hands remain firmly on the plow, my eyes remain fixed on\n'
          'Christ, and my heart remain fully committed to advancing Your kingdom\n'
          'until the day I see You face to face.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 19),
    ),

    // ── 80. LIVING ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'living_in_the',
      theme: 'Living',
      title: 'Living in the Victory of Christ',
      scripture:
          'And they overcame him by the blood of the Lamb and by the word of\n'
          'their testimony, and they did not love their lives to the death.',
      scriptureReference: 'Revelation 12:11',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'Victory Begins with the Blood of the Lamb',
          body:
              'The first reason the believers overcame was not because of their\n'
              'strength, wisdom, or determination, but because of the blood of the\n'
              'Lamb. The blood of Jesus Christ is the foundation of every spiritual\n'
              'victory. Through His sacrifice on the cross, sin was forgiven, Satan\'s\n'
              'accusations were silenced, and the power of death was defeated. Every\n'
              'blessing believers enjoy begins with what Christ accomplished at\n'
              'Calvary.\n'
              'Many Christians strive to overcome life\'s battles through personal\n'
              'effort while forgetting the finished work of Christ. Yet victory has\n'
              'already been secured through His death and resurrection. As Paul\n'
              'declares in Epistle to the Colossians 2:13–15, Christ disarmed the\n'
              'powers of darkness and triumphed over them through the cross. Our\n'
              'confidence rests not in what we can do, but in what Jesus has already\n'
              'done.\n'
              'The blood of Christ is not merely the beginning of your salvation—it\n'
              'is the foundation of your daily victory.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'Your Testimony Declares God\'s Faithfulness',
          body:
              'The believers also overcame by "the word of their testimony." A\n'
              'testimony is more than a personal story; it is a public declaration of\n'
              'God\'s faithfulness and transforming power. Every time believers speak\n'
              'about God\'s goodness, His deliverance, and His grace, they strengthen\n'
              'their own faith and encourage others to trust Him.\n'
              'The enemy desires to silence believers through fear, shame, or\n'
              'discouragement because he knows that a testimony glorifies God and\n'
              'weakens his influence. Yet every life changed by Christ becomes\n'
              'evidence that God\'s power is still at work. As David declares in Book\n'
              'of Psalms 66:16, "Come and hear, all you who fear God, and I will\n'
              'declare what He has done for my soul." A testimony reminds both the\n'
              'speaker and the listener that God is faithful.\n'
              'Your testimony is one of the strongest witnesses that Christ is alive\n'
              'and working today.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'Spiritual Victory Requires Courageous Faith',
          body:
              'The believers overcame because they refused to compromise, even when\n'
              'facing persecution. Their faith was not based on comfort or\n'
              'convenience but on complete confidence in Christ. They understood that\n'
              'temporary suffering could never compare with the eternal glory\n'
              'awaiting them.\n'
              'The enemy often attacks through fear, intimidation, and compromise.\n'
              'He seeks to convince believers that following Christ is too costly.\n'
              'But God\'s Spirit empowers His people to stand firm. As Paul reminds\n'
              'Timothy in Second Epistle to Timothy 1:7, God has not given us a\n'
              'spirit of fear, but of power, love, and a sound mind. Courage grows\n'
              'when believers remember who has already won the battle.\n'
              'Faith is not the absence of fear—it is choosing to trust Christ in\n'
              'the midst of it.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'Eternal Perspective Produces Faithful Living',
          body:
              'The verse says they "did not love their lives to the death." This\n'
              'does not mean believers despise life; it means they value Christ above\n'
              'everything else. Their greatest treasure was not earthly security but\n'
              'eternal fellowship with God. Because their hearts were fixed on\n'
              'eternity, they were able to remain faithful regardless of the cost.\n'
              'Many believers struggle because they become overly attached to\n'
              'temporary things. Yet Jesus continually calls His followers to seek\n'
              'first His kingdom. As He teaches in Gospel of Matthew 16:25, whoever\n'
              'loses his life for Christ\'s sake will truly find it. An eternal\n'
              'perspective transforms the way believers face sacrifice, hardship, and\n'
              'even death.\n'
              'Those who treasure Christ above all else cannot be conquered by the\n'
              'fears of this world.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Every Believer Is Called to Live as an Overcomer',
          body:
              'Revelation does not describe victory as something reserved for a few\n'
              'extraordinary believers. Every follower of Christ is called to live as\n'
              'an overcomer. This victory is experienced daily as believers trust in\n'
              'Christ\'s finished work, stand upon His Word, boldly share their\n'
              'testimony, and remain faithful through every trial.\n'
              'Although spiritual battles continue, believers do not fight for\n'
              'victory—they fight from the victory Christ has already secured. As\n'
              'Paul triumphantly declares in First Epistle to the Corinthians 15:57,\n'
              'thanks be to God, who gives us the victory through our Lord Jesus\n'
              'Christ. Every challenge becomes another opportunity to demonstrate the\n'
              'triumph of God\'s grace.\n'
              'Overcomers are not people who never face battles—they are people who\n'
              'never stop trusting the One who has already overcome.\n'
              '---',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'Your victory is not built upon your strength—it is secured by the\n'
          'blood of Jesus. Your testimony proclaims His faithfulness, your faith\n'
          'defeats fear, and your eternal hope gives you courage to stand firm\n'
          'until the end. ---',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Am I relying on Christ\'s finished work or on my own strength?',
        'How has God\'s faithfulness shaped the testimony of my life?',
        'Is there an area where fear is keeping me from living boldly for\n'
        'Christ?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for the precious blood of Jesus Christ, through which I\n'
          'have forgiveness, freedom, and victory. Thank You that the battle has\n'
          'already been won through the cross and that I do not have to live in\n'
          'fear of the enemy.\n'
          'Help me never lose confidence in the power of Christ\'s sacrifice.\n'
          'Give me courage to share my testimony and boldly declare Your goodness\n'
          'wherever You place me. Let my life continually point others to the\n'
          'grace and faithfulness You have shown me.\n'
          'Strengthen me to stand firm when trials, temptations, or opposition\n'
          'arise. Keep my heart focused on eternity and teach me to value Your\n'
          'kingdom above every temporary comfort. Fill me with the power of Your\n'
          'Holy Spirit so that I may live each day as an overcomer.\n'
          'May my confidence always rest in the blood of the Lamb, my voice\n'
          'continually proclaim Your faithfulness, and my life faithfully reflect\n'
          'the victory that is mine through Jesus Christ.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 20),
    ),

    // ── 81. BEAUTY ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'beauty_from_ashes',
      theme: 'Beauty',
      title: 'Beauty from Ashes',
      scripture:
          'To console those who mourn in Zion, to give them beauty for ashes,\n'
          'the oil of joy for mourning, the garment of praise for the spirit of\n'
          'heaviness; that they may be called trees of righteousness, the\n'
          'planting of the Lord, that He may be glorified.',
      scriptureReference: 'Isaiah 61:3',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'God Specializes in Divine Restoration',
          body:
              'Isaiah reveals one of the most beautiful promises in Scripture: God\n'
              'exchanges ashes for beauty. Ashes symbolize loss, grief, brokenness,\n'
              'disappointment, and the painful consequences of life\'s struggles. Yet\n'
              'God does not leave His children sitting in the ashes of despair. He is\n'
              'a God of restoration who delights in rebuilding what has been broken\n'
              'and renewing what seems beyond repair.\n'
              'Many believers carry the ashes of broken dreams, painful memories,\n'
              'failures, or deep disappointments. The enemy whispers that those\n'
              'losses define their future. But God speaks a different word. He\n'
              'restores what sin, suffering, and sorrow have stolen. As the prophet\n'
              'declares in Book of Joel 2:25, God is able to restore the years the\n'
              'locust has eaten. No life is too damaged for His restoring grace.\n'
              'God never wastes your brokenness—He transforms it into a testimony of\n'
              'His grace.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'Christ Replaces Mourning with Lasting Joy',
          body:
              'Isaiah promises "the oil of joy for mourning." Mourning is a natural\n'
              'response to pain, loss, and disappointment, but God never intended\n'
              'sorrow to become the permanent condition of His children. Through His\n'
              'presence, He brings comfort that reaches the deepest places of the\n'
              'heart and joy that circumstances cannot destroy.\n'
              'Joy is not the denial of pain; it is the assurance that God remains\n'
              'faithful in the middle of it. Even when tears continue for a season,\n'
              'His comfort sustains His people. As David proclaims in Book of Psalms\n'
              '30:5, weeping may endure for a night, but joy comes in the morning.\n'
              'God\'s timing is always perfect, and His comfort never fails.\n'
              'The God who allows seasons of mourning is also the God who brings\n'
              'lasting joy.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'Praise Breaks the Weight of Discouragement',
          body:
              'God offers "the garment of praise for the spirit of heaviness." A\n'
              'spirit of heaviness often brings discouragement, fear, anxiety,\n'
              'hopelessness, and spiritual weariness. One of God\'s powerful remedies\n'
              'is praise. Praise shifts the believer\'s focus from the size of the\n'
              'problem to the greatness of God.\n'
              'The enemy desires to keep believers overwhelmed by fear and despair\n'
              'because discouraged hearts often struggle to trust God\'s promises. But\n'
              'praise changes the atmosphere of the soul. It reminds us of God\'s\n'
              'faithfulness and renews our confidence in His power. As Paul and Silas\n'
              'demonstrated in Acts of the Apostles 16:25–26, worship in the darkest\n'
              'moments can become the doorway through which God displays His power.\n'
              'Praise does not ignore your circumstances—it declares that God is\n'
              'greater than them.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'God Plants His People to Stand Strong',
          body:
              'Isaiah says God\'s restored people will become "trees of\n'
              'righteousness, the planting of the Lord." A healthy tree does not\n'
              'become strong overnight. It grows deep roots through every season,\n'
              'drawing nourishment from the soil even during storms. Likewise, God\n'
              'desires His people to become spiritually mature, deeply rooted in His\n'
              'truth, and steadfast through every trial.\n'
              'Storms do not uproot trees with deep roots, and life\'s difficulties\n'
              'cannot easily shake believers who remain rooted in Christ. As David\n'
              'describes in Book of Psalms 1:2–3, the one who delights in God\'s Word\n'
              'is like a tree planted by streams of water, continually bearing fruit.\n'
              'God\'s restoration is not temporary—it establishes believers in lasting\n'
              'strength.\n'
              'Those whom God plants cannot be easily uprooted by the storms of\n'
              'life.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Your Restored Life Brings Glory to God',
          body:
              'Isaiah concludes by revealing God\'s ultimate purpose: "that He may be\n'
              'glorified." Restoration is never merely for personal comfort. God\n'
              'heals, strengthens, and restores His people so that their transformed\n'
              'lives become living testimonies of His goodness, mercy, and power.\n'
              'Every life changed by God\'s grace points others to His glory.\n'
              'When people see hope rising from despair, joy replacing sorrow, and\n'
              'faith overcoming brokenness, they witness the work of God. As Jesus\n'
              'teaches in Gospel of Matthew 5:16, believers are called to let their\n'
              'light shine so that others may glorify the Father in heaven. Your\n'
              'story of restoration may become the encouragement someone else\n'
              'desperately needs.\n'
              'God restores your life not only for your blessing, but so the world\n'
              'can see His greatness.',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'God is the only One who can take ashes and create beauty. He turns\n'
          'mourning into joy, heaviness into praise, and broken lives into living\n'
          'testimonies of His glory. What the enemy intended to destroy, God\n'
          'transforms into something beautiful for His kingdom.',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'What ashes or broken places in my life do I need to surrender to God?',
        'Have I allowed discouragement to silence my praise?',
        'How can my story of God\'s restoration bring hope and glory to Him?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for being the God of restoration. Thank You that You never\n'
          'leave me in the ashes of disappointment, grief, or failure, but\n'
          'lovingly transform my brokenness into something beautiful for Your\n'
          'glory.\n'
          'Heal every wounded place in my heart. Replace my sorrow with the joy\n'
          'that comes from Your presence, and clothe me with a spirit of praise\n'
          'whenever discouragement tries to overwhelm me. Help me trust that You\n'
          'are working even when I cannot yet see the beauty You are creating.\n'
          'Plant me deeply in Your truth so that I may remain strong through\n'
          'every season of life. Let my life bear the fruit of righteousness and\n'
          'become a testimony of Your grace to everyone around me. Use my story\n'
          'to encourage the broken, strengthen the weary, and point others to\n'
          'Jesus Christ.\n'
          'May my life continually reflect this wonderful truth: that the God\n'
          'who restores hearts also restores hope, and that every work of\n'
          'restoration ultimately brings glory to Your holy name.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 21),
    ),

    // ── 82. THE ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'the_sacrifice_god',
      theme: 'The',
      title: 'The Sacrifice God Will Never Reject',
      scripture:
          'The sacrifices of God are a broken spirit, a broken and a contrite\n'
          'heart—These, O God, You will not despise.',
      scriptureReference: 'Psalms 51:17',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'God Desires the Heart Above All Else',
          body:
              'Psalm 51 was written after David\'s repentance following his sin with\n'
              'Bathsheba. Although he had once offered many sacrifices to God, David\n'
              'realized that no outward offering could restore a broken relationship\n'
              'with the Lord. What God truly desired was not another sacrifice on the\n'
              'altar but genuine repentance within the heart.\n'
              'It is possible to perform religious activities while remaining\n'
              'spiritually distant from God. We may attend church, pray, sing worship\n'
              'songs, or serve in ministry, yet still hold onto pride, unforgiveness,\n'
              'or hidden sin. God is never impressed by outward appearances alone. As\n'
              'the Lord told Samuel in Book of First Samuel 16:7, people look at the\n'
              'outward appearance, but the Lord looks at the heart. The condition of\n'
              'our heart matters more to God than the appearance of our actions.\n'
              'God is not seeking perfect performances—He is seeking surrendered\n'
              'hearts.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'Brokenness Opens the Door to God\'s Grace',
          body:
              'David speaks of "a broken spirit." Spiritual brokenness is not\n'
              'weakness or hopelessness; it is the humble recognition of our need for\n'
              'God. It is the place where pride is laid down, self-sufficiency is\n'
              'abandoned, and the soul fully depends upon God\'s mercy.\n'
              'The world often teaches people to hide their weaknesses and project\n'
              'strength, but God\'s kingdom works differently. He pours His grace into\n'
              'hearts that acknowledge their need for Him. As James writes in Epistle\n'
              'of James 4:6, God resists the proud but gives grace to the humble.\n'
              'Brokenness is not the end of God\'s work—it is often where His greatest\n'
              'work begins.\n'
              'The heart that humbly bows before God is the heart He delights to\n'
              'restore.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'Genuine Repentance Leads to Transformation',
          body:
              'David also speaks of "a contrite heart." Contrition goes beyond\n'
              'feeling guilty about sin. It is a sincere sorrow that leads to genuine\n'
              'repentance and a desire to turn away from everything that dishonors\n'
              'God. True repentance does not merely seek forgiveness; it longs for\n'
              'transformation.\n'
              'The enemy often traps believers in either pride or condemnation.\n'
              'Pride refuses to admit sin, while condemnation believes forgiveness is\n'
              'impossible. The Gospel offers a better way. When we sincerely confess\n'
              'our sins, God responds with mercy and cleansing. As John assures\n'
              'believers in First Epistle of John 1:9, if we confess our sins, God is\n'
              'faithful and just to forgive us and cleanse us from all\n'
              'unrighteousness.\n'
              'God never rejects those who sincerely turn back to Him.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'God\'s Mercy Is Greater Than Our Failures',
          body:
              'David had committed serious sins, yet he discovered that God\'s mercy\n'
              'was greater than his deepest failures. This psalm reminds believers\n'
              'that no mistake is too great for God\'s grace when there is genuine\n'
              'repentance. God\'s forgiveness restores what sin has broken and renews\n'
              'the fellowship that guilt has damaged.\n'
              'Many believers continue carrying shame long after God has offered\n'
              'forgiveness. They struggle to believe that God could still love or use\n'
              'them. Yet throughout Scripture, God repeatedly restores those who\n'
              'return to Him with humble hearts. Peter denied Christ, yet Jesus\n'
              'restored him and entrusted him with ministry. As David declares\n'
              'earlier in Book of Psalms 51:1, God\'s lovingkindness and abundant\n'
              'mercy are greater than every transgression.\n'
              'Your greatest failure is never greater than God\'s greatest mercy.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'A Humble Heart Remains Close to God',
          body:
              'A broken and contrite heart is not something believers experience\n'
              'only once at conversion. It is an attitude that should characterize\n'
              'the Christian life. Humility keeps the heart sensitive to God\'s voice,\n'
              'quick to repent, and eager to obey. Those who remain humble continue\n'
              'growing in intimacy with God because they never lose their awareness\n'
              'of His grace.\n'
              'The longer we walk with God, the greater the temptation to rely upon\n'
              'our own spiritual achievements. Yet true maturity produces greater\n'
              'humility, not greater pride. As Isaiah records in Book of Isaiah 66:2,\n'
              'God looks with favor upon those who are humble, contrite in spirit,\n'
              'and who tremble at His Word. A humble heart remains fertile ground for\n'
              'God\'s continued work.\n'
              'The closer you draw to God, the more precious humility becomes.',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'God is not searching for impressive sacrifices—He is searching for\n'
          'surrendered hearts. He never rejects the person who comes with genuine\n'
          'repentance, because His mercy is always greater than our failures, and\n'
          'His grace is always ready to restore.',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Is there any area of my heart that I have been unwilling to surrender\n'
        'to God?',
        'Have I confused religious activity with genuine intimacy with the\n'
        'Lord?',
        'Am I living in the freedom of God\'s forgiveness, or am I still\n'
        'carrying unnecessary guilt and shame?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for Your endless mercy and unfailing love. Thank You that\n'
          'You do not reject those who come before You with humble and repentant\n'
          'hearts. Thank You that Your grace is greater than my failures and Your\n'
          'forgiveness is deeper than my sin.\n'
          'Search my heart and reveal anything that displeases You. Remove every\n'
          'trace of pride, self-reliance, and hidden sin. Create within me a\n'
          'broken spirit that depends completely upon Your grace and a contrite\n'
          'heart that quickly responds to Your correction.\n'
          'Help me never substitute religious activity for a genuine\n'
          'relationship with You. Teach me to walk in humility every day,\n'
          'remembering that every blessing in my life comes from Your mercy\n'
          'alone. Fill me with the joy of Your forgiveness and restore the\n'
          'closeness that comes from living in honest fellowship with You.\n'
          'May my greatest offering always be a heart fully surrendered to You,\n'
          'and may my life continually reflect the beauty of Your restoring grace\n'
          'and unfailing mercy.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 22),
    ),

    // ── 83. LIVING ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'living_free_from',
      theme: 'Living',
      title: 'Living Free from Condemnation',
      scripture:
          'There is therefore now no condemnation to those who are in Christ\n'
          'Jesus, who do not walk according to the flesh, but according to the\n'
          'Spirit.',
      scriptureReference: 'Romans 8:1',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'Christ Has Removed Every Condemnation',
          body:
              'Romans 8:1 begins with one of the greatest declarations of hope in\n'
              'all of Scripture: "There is therefore now no condemnation." Through\n'
              'the death and resurrection of Jesus Christ, every believer who has\n'
              'placed their faith in Him has been completely forgiven and declared\n'
              'righteous before God. The guilt of sin has been removed, and the\n'
              'sentence against us has been cancelled by the finished work of Christ.\n'
              'Many believers continue living under the weight of past failures,\n'
              'believing they must somehow earn God\'s acceptance. Yet the Gospel\n'
              'declares that Christ has already paid the full price for sin. As Paul\n'
              'writes in Epistle to the Colossians 2:13–14, God forgave all our\n'
              'trespasses by canceling the record of debt that stood against us. The\n'
              'cross did not merely reduce our guilt—it completely removed our\n'
              'condemnation.\n'
              'When Christ says you are forgiven, no accusation can overturn His\n'
              'verdict.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'Your Position Is Secure in Christ',
          body:
              'Paul carefully says there is no condemnation "to those who are in\n'
              'Christ Jesus." This phrase speaks of the believer\'s new identity and\n'
              'relationship with God. To be "in Christ" means we are united with Him\n'
              'through faith. His righteousness becomes our righteousness, His\n'
              'victory becomes our victory, and His relationship with the Father\n'
              'becomes our privilege.\n'
              'The enemy continually tries to define believers by their past\n'
              'mistakes, weaknesses, and failures. But God defines them by their\n'
              'union with His Son. As Paul declares in Second Epistle to the\n'
              'Corinthians 5:17, anyone who is in Christ is a new creation; the old\n'
              'has passed away, and the new has come. Our identity is no longer\n'
              'rooted in who we were but in who Christ has made us to be.\n'
              'Your past may explain your story, but it no longer defines your\n'
              'identity.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'Conviction Leads to Freedom, Condemnation Leads to Bondage',
          body:
              'There is an important difference between the conviction of the Holy\n'
              'Spirit and the condemnation of the enemy. The Holy Spirit lovingly\n'
              'convicts believers of sin so they may repent, be restored, and grow\n'
              'closer to God. Condemnation, however, seeks to produce shame,\n'
              'hopelessness, and distance from God by convincing believers they are\n'
              'beyond His grace.\n'
              'Satan is called the accuser of the brethren because he constantly\n'
              'reminds God\'s people of their failures. But Jesus stands as their\n'
              'Advocate before the Father. As John assures believers in First Epistle\n'
              'of John 2:1–2, if anyone sins, we have an Advocate with the\n'
              'Father—Jesus Christ the righteous. God\'s conviction restores, while\n'
              'Satan\'s condemnation enslaves.\n'
              'The voice that draws you back to God is from the Holy Spirit; the\n'
              'voice that drives you away from Him is not.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'Walking by the Spirit Leads to Victory',
          body:
              'Paul explains that those who belong to Christ walk according to the\n'
              'Spirit rather than according to the flesh. This does not mean\n'
              'believers become sinlessly perfect, but that the direction of their\n'
              'lives is guided by the Holy Spirit. Through His power, they are\n'
              'enabled to overcome sinful desires and increasingly reflect the\n'
              'character of Christ.\n'
              'Many Christians try to overcome sin through willpower alone and\n'
              'become discouraged when they fail. But lasting victory is found by\n'
              'depending upon the Holy Spirit. As Paul teaches in Epistle to the\n'
              'Galatians 5:16, those who walk in the Spirit will not fulfill the\n'
              'desires of the flesh. Spiritual growth is not achieved by striving\n'
              'harder but by surrendering more fully to God\'s Spirit.\n'
              'Freedom from condemnation is meant to lead us into a life of joyful\n'
              'obedience, not careless living.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Live in the Freedom Christ Has Purchased',
          body:
              'Because there is no condemnation in Christ, believers no longer have\n'
              'to live under fear, guilt, or constant insecurity. They are free to\n'
              'approach God with confidence, knowing they are loved, accepted, and\n'
              'secure in His grace. This freedom produces gratitude, worship, and a\n'
              'deeper desire to honor the One who has redeemed them.\n'
              'The Christian life is not about continually trying to earn God\'s\n'
              'approval—it is about living from the approval already secured through\n'
              'Christ. As the writer of Epistle to the Hebrews 4:16 encourages,\n'
              'believers can boldly approach the throne of grace to receive mercy and\n'
              'find grace in time of need. The Father welcomes His children because\n'
              'they come through His Son.\n'
              'Those who understand God\'s grace no longer live as prisoners of\n'
              'guilt—they live as sons and daughters of the King.',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'The cross has already spoken. Your guilt has been forgiven. Your debt\n'
          'has been paid. Your condemnation has been removed. When you are in\n'
          'Christ, you no longer live under the sentence of your past— you live\n'
          'under the grace of your Savior.',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Am I living in the freedom of Christ\'s forgiveness, or am I still\n'
        'carrying guilt that He has already removed?',
        'Can I recognize the difference between the Holy Spirit\'s loving\n'
        'conviction and the enemy\'s condemning accusations?',
        'What would change in my daily walk if I truly believed there is no\n'
        'condemnation for me in Christ?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for the wonderful truth that there is now no condemnation\n'
          'for those who are in Christ Jesus. Thank You for sending Your Son to\n'
          'bear my sins, cancel my debt, and give me a new life through Your\n'
          'amazing grace.\n'
          'Forgive me for the times I have continued to carry guilt and shame\n'
          'that You have already removed. Help me reject every lie of the enemy\n'
          'that tells me I am unworthy of Your love. Teach me to rest confidently\n'
          'in the finished work of Jesus Christ.\n'
          'Fill me with Your Holy Spirit and lead me each day in paths of\n'
          'righteousness. Help me walk in joyful obedience, not because I am\n'
          'trying to earn Your acceptance, but because I have already been\n'
          'accepted through Christ. Let my life reflect the freedom, peace, and\n'
          'confidence that come from knowing I belong to You.\n'
          'May I never forget that I have been completely forgiven, fully\n'
          'accepted, and forever loved through Jesus Christ, and may I live each\n'
          'day in the glorious freedom of Your saving grace.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 23),
    ),

    // ── 84. FAITH ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'faith_refined_by',
      theme: 'Faith',
      title: 'Faith Refined by the Fire',
      scripture:
          'That the genuineness of your faith, being much more precious than\n'
          'gold that perishes, though it is tested by fire, may be found to\n'
          'praise, honor, and glory at the revelation of Jesus Christ.',
      scriptureReference: '1 Peter 1:7',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'Trials Reveal the Authenticity of Faith',
          body:
              'Peter explains that trials serve a divine purpose—they reveal the\n'
              'genuineness of our faith. Just as gold is tested by fire to prove its\n'
              'purity, God allows seasons of testing to expose whether our trust\n'
              'rests in Him or merely in favorable circumstances. Genuine faith does\n'
              'not disappear when life becomes difficult; it grows stronger because\n'
              'it is anchored in the unchanging character of God.\n'
              'Many believers wonder why God allows painful seasons. While He does\n'
              'not delight in our suffering, He uses it to accomplish something far\n'
              'greater than temporary comfort. Trials expose hidden fears, strengthen\n'
              'dependence upon Him, and reveal the reality of our faith. As James\n'
              'writes in Epistle of James 1:2–3, the testing of faith produces\n'
              'perseverance. Every trial becomes an opportunity for faith to become\n'
              'deeper and more genuine.\n'
              'Faith is not proven on easy days—it is revealed in difficult ones.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'Your Faith Is More Precious Than Gold',
          body:
              'Peter compares faith to gold but quickly says that genuine faith is\n'
              'far more valuable. Gold is one of the world\'s most treasured\n'
              'possessions, yet it is temporary and will one day perish. Faith,\n'
              'however, has eternal value because it connects believers to Christ and\n'
              'secures an inheritance that can never fade away.\n'
              'The world often measures wealth by possessions, achievements, or\n'
              'status, but heaven measures wealth differently. A believer with\n'
              'genuine faith possesses something that cannot be bought, stolen, or\n'
              'destroyed. As the writer of Epistle to the Hebrews 11:6 reminds us,\n'
              'without faith it is impossible to please God. Faith is precious\n'
              'because it allows us to know, trust, and walk with the living God.\n'
              'The greatest treasure you possess is not found in your hands—it is\n'
              'found in your faith.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'The Fire Is Designed to Refine, Not Destroy',
          body:
              'Peter says faith is "tested by fire." Fire does not create gold—it\n'
              'removes impurities from it. Likewise, trials do not create faith; they\n'
              'refine the faith that God has already planted within the believer.\n'
              'Through testing, pride is replaced with humility, self-reliance gives\n'
              'way to dependence on God, and temporary priorities are exchanged for\n'
              'eternal ones.\n'
              'The enemy wants believers to believe that the fire means God has\n'
              'abandoned them. But throughout Scripture, God has often met His people\n'
              'in the middle of the fire. The three Hebrew men experienced God\'s\n'
              'presence in the fiery furnace, not outside of it. As Isaiah declares\n'
              'in Book of Isaiah 43:2, when God\'s people pass through the fire, He is\n'
              'with them, and they will not be consumed.\n'
              'God does not send you into the fire to destroy your faith—He uses it\n'
              'to purify it.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'Every Trial Has an Eternal Purpose',
          body:
              'Peter reminds believers that refined faith will result in praise,\n'
              'honor, and glory when Jesus Christ is revealed. This means that\n'
              'present trials must always be viewed through the lens of eternity. The\n'
              'pain believers experience today is preparing them for an eternal\n'
              'reward that far outweighs every temporary hardship.\n'
              'It is easy to become discouraged when we focus only on present\n'
              'difficulties. But God\'s perspective reaches beyond today\'s struggles\n'
              'to tomorrow\'s glory. As Paul writes in Second Epistle to the\n'
              'Corinthians 4:17–18, our light and momentary afflictions are producing\n'
              'an eternal weight of glory that far surpasses them all. Heaven gives\n'
              'meaning to every faithful step taken on earth.\n'
              'The fire of today is preparing you for the glory of tomorrow.',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Keep Your Eyes on Jesus Through Every Test',
          body:
              'Peter points believers to "the revelation of Jesus Christ." The\n'
              'ultimate goal of the Christian life is not simply surviving trials but\n'
              'becoming more like Christ and one day seeing Him face to face. Every\n'
              'trial invites believers to keep their eyes fixed on Jesus rather than\n'
              'becoming overwhelmed by their circumstances.\n'
              'When Peter walked on the water, he remained steady while his eyes\n'
              'were on Jesus, but he began to sink when he focused on the storm. The\n'
              'same principle applies today. As the writer of Epistle to the Hebrews\n'
              '12:2 encourages, believers are to fix their eyes on Jesus, the author\n'
              'and finisher of their faith. A Christ-centered focus produces\n'
              'steadfast faith even in life\'s fiercest storms.\n'
              'The strength to endure every trial is found by keeping your eyes on\n'
              'the Savior rather than the storm.',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'The fire is not your enemy—it is God\'s instrument of refinement. Your\n'
          'faith is more valuable than gold, your trials are not without purpose,\n'
          'and every test is preparing you to bring glory to Christ when He is\n'
          'revealed.',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'What trial is God using to strengthen and refine my faith today?',
        'Am I focusing more on the fire or on the God who walks with me\n'
        'through it?',
        'How can I keep my eyes fixed on Christ instead of becoming\n'
        'discouraged by my circumstances?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for reminding me that my faith is precious in Your sight\n'
          'and that every trial has a purpose in Your perfect plan. Thank You\n'
          'that You never waste my pain but use it to refine my character and\n'
          'draw me closer to You.\n'
          'Help me trust You when the fire of testing becomes intense. Remove\n'
          'every impurity from my heart—pride, fear, doubt, and self-reliance—and\n'
          'replace them with deeper faith, greater humility, and unwavering\n'
          'confidence in Your promises.\n'
          'Teach me to value eternal treasures more than temporary comforts.\n'
          'When I grow weary, remind me that You are walking with me through\n'
          'every trial and that Your grace is sufficient for every season. Keep\n'
          'my eyes fixed on Jesus and fill my heart with hope as I look forward\n'
          'to the day when I will see Him face to face.\n'
          'May every trial strengthen my faith, every challenge deepen my trust,\n'
          'and every victory bring praise, honor, and glory to my Lord and\n'
          'Savior, Jesus Christ.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 24),
    ),

    // ── 85. DWELLING ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'dwelling_in_the',
      theme: 'Dwelling',
      title: 'Dwelling in the Secret Place of God',
      scripture:
          'He who dwells in the secret place of the Most High shall abide under\n'
          'the shadow of the Almighty.',
      scriptureReference: 'Psalms 91:1',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'God\'s Presence Is Meant to Be Our Dwelling Place',
          body:
              'Psalm 91 begins with an invitation, not merely a promise. The\n'
              'blessing is for those who "dwell" in the secret place of the Most\n'
              'High. To dwell means to remain, live, and continually abide in God\'s\n'
              'presence. It speaks of a lifestyle of intimate fellowship rather than\n'
              'occasional visits during times of crisis. God desires to be more than\n'
              'a refuge we seek in emergencies; He desires to become the home where\n'
              'our souls continually rest.\n'
              'Many believers only seek God when life becomes difficult. Yet God\n'
              'longs for daily communion with His children. As Jesus taught in Gospel\n'
              'of John 15:4, believers are called to abide in Him just as a branch\n'
              'remains connected to the vine. Strength, peace, and spiritual fruit\n'
              'flow naturally from a life that continually remains close to God.\n'
              'The safest place on earth is not a location—it is a life that\n'
              'continually dwells in the presence of God.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'The Secret Place Is Built Through Intimacy',
          body:
              'The "secret place" is not a hidden geographical location but a\n'
              'personal relationship with God. It is the quiet place of prayer,\n'
              'worship, meditation on His Word, and complete dependence upon Him. It\n'
              'is where hearts are transformed, burdens are surrendered, and faith is\n'
              'strengthened. The secret place is where believers learn to hear God\'s\n'
              'voice above every other voice.\n'
              'In a noisy world filled with distractions, many believers struggle to\n'
              'cultivate intimacy with God. Yet it is in quiet fellowship that\n'
              'spiritual strength is renewed. As David wrote in Book of Psalms 27:4,\n'
              'his greatest desire was to dwell in the house of the Lord and behold\n'
              'His beauty. Intimacy with God is not reserved for a few—it is the\n'
              'privilege of every believer.\n'
              'The deeper your fellowship with God becomes, the stronger your faith\n'
              'will grow.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'Under God\'s Shadow There Is Protection',
          body:
              'The psalmist declares that those who dwell with God "shall abide\n'
              'under the shadow of the Almighty." A shadow exists because someone\n'
              'greater is standing nearby. God\'s shadow represents His constant\n'
              'presence, protection, and covering over His people. His protection\n'
              'does not remove every trial, but it assures believers that they are\n'
              'never abandoned or beyond His care.\n'
              'Throughout Scripture, God repeatedly demonstrated His protective hand\n'
              'over His people. He shielded Israel in the wilderness, preserved\n'
              'Daniel in the lions\' den, and strengthened Paul through persecution.\n'
              'As the Lord declared through Book of Isaiah 43:2, when His people pass\n'
              'through waters or fire, He promises to be with them. His presence is\n'
              'the believer\'s greatest security.\n'
              'The safest shelter is not found in favorable circumstances but\n'
              'beneath the shadow of the Almighty.\n'
              '—',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'Trust Grows Through Daily Fellowship',
          body:
              'Dwelling with God produces confidence because relationship replaces\n'
              'uncertainty. The more believers spend time in His presence, the more\n'
              'they discover His faithfulness, wisdom, and love. Trust is not built\n'
              'overnight; it grows through consistent fellowship with the One who\n'
              'never changes.\n'
              'Many people try to develop faith only after problems arise. But faith\n'
              'is strengthened long before the storm arrives. Daily prayer, worship,\n'
              'and meditation on Scripture prepare the heart to remain steadfast\n'
              'during difficult seasons. As the prophet declared in Book of Isaiah\n'
              '26:3, God keeps in perfect peace those whose minds remain fixed upon\n'
              'Him because they trust in Him.\n'
              'Those who dwell with God during peaceful seasons will discover His\n'
              'peace during difficult seasons.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'A Life That Abides Becomes a Life That Overcomes',
          body:
              'Psalm 91 is filled with promises of protection, deliverance, and\n'
              'peace, but they begin with one simple condition: dwelling in God\'s\n'
              'presence. Victory over fear, anxiety, temptation, and discouragement\n'
              'is not found through human effort but through continual fellowship\n'
              'with the Lord. Those who abide in Him discover that His strength\n'
              'becomes their strength.\n'
              'Every day presents a fresh invitation to enter God\'s presence and\n'
              'remain there. No matter how busy life becomes, the greatest priority\n'
              'remains knowing Him. As the writer of Epistle to the Hebrews 10:22\n'
              'reminds believers, they are invited to draw near to God with sincere\n'
              'hearts and full assurance of faith. Those who remain near to God will\n'
              'never lack His grace for the journey.\n'
              'A believer who lives in God\'s presence will always find strength for\n'
              'life\'s battles.\n'
              '---',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'The greatest promise of Psalm 91 is not merely protection—it is God\'s\n'
          'presence. When you make Him your dwelling place, His peace becomes\n'
          'your covering, His strength becomes your confidence, and His presence\n'
          'becomes your greatest refuge. ---',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Is God\'s presence my daily dwelling place or only my emergency\n'
        'shelter?',
        'What distractions are keeping me from spending deeper time with the\n'
        'Lord?',
        'How can I intentionally cultivate intimacy with God each day?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for inviting me into the secret place of Your presence.\n'
          'Thank You that You are not only my Creator but also my refuge, my\n'
          'shelter, and my resting place. There is no safer place than abiding\n'
          'close to You.\n'
          'Forgive me for the times I have sought comfort, security, or\n'
          'direction apart from You. Draw my heart back to You each day. Teach me\n'
          'to love Your presence more than the distractions of this world and to\n'
          'make time for prayer, worship, and meditation on Your Word.\n'
          'Help me remain under the shadow of Your Almighty care. When fear\n'
          'rises, remind me that You are my refuge. When uncertainty comes,\n'
          'strengthen my faith through Your promises. Let my relationship with\n'
          'You grow deeper until Your peace guards my heart and Your presence\n'
          'becomes my greatest joy.\n'
          'May I dwell continually in the secret place of the Most High, rest\n'
          'confidently beneath the shadow of the Almighty, and live each day\n'
          'knowing that my greatest security is found in You alone.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 25),
    ),

    // ── 86. THE ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'the_path_to',
      theme: 'The',
      title: 'The Path to God\'s Exaltation',
      scripture:
          'Therefore humble yourselves under the mighty hand of God, that He may\n'
          'exalt you in due time.',
      scriptureReference: '1 Peter 5:6',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'Humility Is the Doorway to God\'s Grace',
          body:
              'Peter begins with a powerful command: "Humble yourselves under the\n'
              'mighty hand of God." In God\'s kingdom, humility is not weakness but\n'
              'strength under God\'s authority. It is the willingness to acknowledge\n'
              'that God is Lord, His wisdom is perfect, and His plans are greater\n'
              'than our own. Humility positions the heart to receive God\'s grace and\n'
              'guidance.\n'
              'The world often celebrates self-promotion, independence, and personal\n'
              'achievement. However, God\'s kingdom operates differently. Those who\n'
              'humble themselves before Him discover His favor and strength. As James\n'
              'declares in Epistle of James 4:6, God resists the proud but gives\n'
              'grace to the humble. The more we surrender our lives to Him, the more\n'
              'His grace works powerfully within us.\n'
              'True greatness is not found in lifting yourself up but in bowing\n'
              'before God.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'God\'s Mighty Hand Is Both Powerful and Loving',
          body:
              'Peter calls believers to humble themselves under God\'s "mighty hand."\n'
              'Throughout Scripture, God\'s mighty hand represents His power to\n'
              'protect, provide, discipline, and deliver His people. The same hand\n'
              'that parted the Red Sea, sustained Israel in the wilderness, and\n'
              'raised Christ from the dead is the hand that lovingly guides every\n'
              'believer today.\n'
              'There are times when God\'s hand leads us through difficult seasons\n'
              'that we do not fully understand. Yet His mighty hand is never against\n'
              'His children—it is always working for their good. As Paul assures us\n'
              'in Epistle to the Romans 8:28, God works all things together for the\n'
              'good of those who love Him. Even when His ways seem mysterious, His\n'
              'heart remains faithful.\n'
              'The hand that asks for your surrender is the same hand that\n'
              'faithfully sustains your life.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'God\'s Timing Is Always Perfect',
          body:
              'Peter promises that God will exalt His people "in due time." One of\n'
              'the greatest challenges believers face is waiting for God\'s timing. We\n'
              'often desire immediate answers, quick promotions, and instant\n'
              'breakthroughs, but God works according to His perfect schedule rather\n'
              'than our impatient expectations.\n'
              'Waiting seasons are not wasted seasons. They are often times of\n'
              'preparation, refinement, and spiritual growth. Joseph waited in prison\n'
              'before leading Egypt. David waited years before becoming king. Jesus\n'
              'Himself waited until the appointed time to begin His public ministry.\n'
              'As Solomon reminds us in Book of Ecclesiastes 3:11, God makes\n'
              'everything beautiful in its time. His delays are never mistakes—they\n'
              'are part of His perfect plan.\n'
              'God\'s timing is never late because He always works according to\n'
              'perfect wisdom.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'Humility Frees Us from the Burden of Self-Promotion',
          body:
              'Many people exhaust themselves trying to prove their worth, gain\n'
              'recognition, or force open doors that God has not yet opened. Peter\n'
              'teaches believers to leave their promotion in God\'s hands. When God\n'
              'chooses the right time to lift someone up, no human obstacle can\n'
              'prevent His purpose from being fulfilled.\n'
              'The enemy often tempts believers to compare themselves with others or\n'
              'become frustrated when they seem overlooked. But God calls His\n'
              'children to faithfulness rather than competition. As Jesus teaches in\n'
              'Gospel of Matthew 23:12, whoever humbles themselves will be exalted.\n'
              'The safest place is not striving for recognition but faithfully\n'
              'serving where God has placed you.\n'
              'You never have to force what God has already planned for your life.\n'
              '—',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Trust God with Every Season of Your Journey',
          body:
              'Humility ultimately means trusting God enough to place every part of\n'
              'life into His hands. It means believing that He knows what is best,\n'
              'even when we cannot see the full picture. Whether the season is one of\n'
              'waiting, serving, growing, or suffering, God is faithfully working\n'
              'behind the scenes for His glory and our good.\n'
              'The verses that follow encourage believers to cast all their cares\n'
              'upon God because He cares for them. Humility and trust go hand in\n'
              'hand. As David declares in Book of Psalms 37:5, committing your way to\n'
              'the Lord and trusting Him allows Him to bring His purposes to pass. A\n'
              'humble heart rests confidently in God\'s unfailing care.\n'
              'Those who trust God\'s hands never need to fear God\'s timing.\n'
              '---',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'Humility is not thinking less of yourself—it is trusting God more\n'
          'than yourself. When you place your life under God\'s mighty hand, He\n'
          'will lift you up at the perfect time, in the perfect way, for His\n'
          'perfect purpose. ---',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Are there areas of my life where pride is keeping me from fully\n'
        'trusting God?',
        'Am I patiently waiting for God\'s timing, or am I trying to force my\n'
        'own plans?',
        'What would change if I completely surrendered my future into God\'s\n'
        'mighty hand?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for Your mighty hand that protects, guides, and faithfully\n'
          'cares for me. Thank You that You are working in my life even when I\n'
          'cannot see what You are doing. I acknowledge that Your wisdom is\n'
          'greater than mine and Your timing is always perfect.\n'
          'Forgive me for the times I have allowed pride, impatience, or\n'
          'self-reliance to control my decisions. Teach me to humble myself\n'
          'before You each day and to trust Your plans above my own. Help me wait\n'
          'with faith instead of frustration, knowing that You never forget Your\n'
          'promises.\n'
          'Strengthen me to serve faithfully wherever You have placed me. Keep\n'
          'my heart free from comparison and the desire for human recognition.\n'
          'Let my confidence rest in Your approval alone, trusting that You will\n'
          'open every door at the right time.\n'
          'May I gladly live under Your mighty hand, walk humbly before You, and\n'
          'patiently wait for the day You choose to lift me up according to Your\n'
          'perfect will.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 26),
    ),

    // ── 87. A ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'a_heart_that',
      theme: 'A',
      title: 'A Heart That Never Stops Learning',
      scripture:
          'The heart of the prudent acquires knowledge, and the ear of the wise\n'
          'seeks knowledge.',
      scriptureReference: 'Proverbs 18:15',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'Wisdom Begins with a Teachable Heart',
          body:
              'Solomon teaches that the prudent person actively acquires knowledge.\n'
              'This reveals that wisdom is not accidental—it is intentional. A\n'
              'teachable heart recognizes that there is always more to learn from\n'
              'God. Instead of depending on personal understanding, the wise\n'
              'continually seek truth, instruction, and spiritual growth.\n'
              'Many people become stagnant because they believe they already know\n'
              'enough. Pride closes the door to growth, but humility keeps the heart\n'
              'open to God\'s instruction. As Solomon writes in Book of Proverbs 9:9,\n'
              'instruct a wise person and they will become even wiser. Spiritual\n'
              'maturity is marked by a continual desire to grow in the knowledge of\n'
              'God.\n'
              'A teachable heart is fertile ground where God\'s wisdom can flourish.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'God Calls Us to Pursue Knowledge Diligently',
          body:
              'The verse says that the wise "seek" knowledge. Seeking requires\n'
              'effort, consistency, and desire. God has given His Word, His Spirit,\n'
              'and the fellowship of believers so that we may continually grow in\n'
              'understanding. Spiritual wisdom is not gained by passive listening but\n'
              'by actively pursuing God\'s truth.\n'
              'In today\'s world, countless voices compete for our attention. Without\n'
              'discernment, it is easy to absorb opinions while neglecting God\'s\n'
              'truth. As Paul encourages in Second Epistle to Timothy 2:15, believers\n'
              'should diligently present themselves to God, correctly handling the\n'
              'Word of truth. Those who seek God\'s wisdom will never lack direction\n'
              'for life\'s journey.\n'
              'Those who hunger for God\'s truth will continually discover new depths\n'
              'of His wisdom.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'Knowledge Without Obedience Is Incomplete',
          body:
              'Biblical knowledge is never meant to remain merely in the mind. God\n'
              'desires truth that transforms the heart and shapes daily living. The\n'
              'wise seek knowledge because they desire to obey God more faithfully,\n'
              'not simply to accumulate information.\n'
              'Many believers know Scripture but struggle to apply it in practical\n'
              'ways. Genuine wisdom is revealed through obedience. As James teaches\n'
              'in Epistle of James 1:22, believers are called to be doers of the Word\n'
              'and not hearers only. Knowledge becomes wisdom when it is lived out\n'
              'through faithful obedience.\n'
              'The goal of learning God\'s truth is not simply to know more—it is to\n'
              'become more like Christ.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'A Listening Heart Receives God\'s Direction',
          body:
              'Solomon specifically mentions "the ear of the wise." Wise people are\n'
              'known not only for speaking well but for listening carefully. They\n'
              'listen to God\'s voice through Scripture, the guidance of the Holy\n'
              'Spirit, and the wise counsel of mature believers. Listening is one of\n'
              'the greatest expressions of humility.\n'
              'Many mistakes are made because people are quick to speak but slow to\n'
              'listen. Yet God often guides those who quietly seek His direction. As\n'
              'Isaiah declares in Book of Isaiah 30:21, believers hear God\'s voice\n'
              'saying, "This is the way; walk in it." A listening heart becomes a\n'
              'heart that walks confidently in God\'s will.\n'
              'God often speaks most clearly to hearts that are willing to listen.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Lifelong Learning Leads to Lifelong Fruitfulness',
          body:
              'Spiritual growth does not end after salvation. Throughout every\n'
              'season of life, God continues to teach, refine, and prepare His\n'
              'people. Those who remain teachable become increasingly fruitful\n'
              'because they continue growing in wisdom, discernment, and Christlike\n'
              'character.\n'
              'The greatest servants of God never stopped learning from Him. Moses,\n'
              'David, Paul, and the apostles continually sought God\'s wisdom\n'
              'throughout their lives. As Peter encourages in Second Epistle of Peter\n'
              '3:18, believers are to grow in the grace and knowledge of our Lord and\n'
              'Savior Jesus Christ. A growing believer becomes a fruitful believer.\n'
              'The moment you stop learning from God is the moment you stop growing\n'
              'in Him.\n'
              '---',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'God does not reserve His wisdom for the naturally intelligent—He\n'
          'gives it to the humble who seek Him. A heart that remains teachable,\n'
          'an ear that continually listens, and a life that faithfully obeys will\n'
          'continually grow in the wisdom of God. ---',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Do I approach God\'s Word with a teachable and humble heart?',
        'Am I intentionally seeking God\'s wisdom each day or relying on my own\n'
        'understanding?',
        'What truth has God been teaching me that I need to put into practice?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for being the source of all wisdom and truth. Thank You for\n'
          'giving me Your Word, Your Holy Spirit, and the privilege of growing in\n'
          'the knowledge of You each day.\n'
          'Forgive me for the times I have relied on my own understanding\n'
          'instead of seeking Your wisdom. Remove every trace of pride that keeps\n'
          'me from learning, and give me a humble and teachable heart. Help me\n'
          'hunger for Your truth more than the opinions of this world.\n'
          'Open my ears to hear Your voice and my heart to receive Your\n'
          'instruction. Teach me not only to understand Your Word but also to\n'
          'faithfully obey it in every area of my life. Let Your wisdom guide my\n'
          'decisions, shape my character, and strengthen my faith.\n'
          'May I never stop seeking You, never stop learning from You, and never\n'
          'stop growing into the person You have called me to be.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 27),
    ),

    // ── 88. SANCTIFIED ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    DevotionalModel(
      id: 'sanctified_by_the',
      theme: 'Sanctified',
      title: 'Sanctified by the Truth',
      scripture:
          'Sanctify them by Your truth. Your word is truth.',
      scriptureReference: 'John 17:17',
      sections: const [
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔑',
          heading:
              'God\'s Word Is the Standard of Absolute Truth',
          body:
              'Jesus prayed these words to the Father shortly before going to the\n'
              'cross. In a world filled with changing opinions, cultural\n'
              'philosophies, and human reasoning, Jesus declared that God\'s Word\n'
              'alone is absolute truth. Truth is not determined by popular opinion or\n'
              'personal preference; it is established by God\'s unchanging character\n'
              'and revealed through His Word.\n'
              'Today, many voices compete for our attention, offering conflicting\n'
              'ideas about life, purpose, and morality. Without God\'s truth, people\n'
              'are easily led astray. Yet Scripture remains the unchanging foundation\n'
              'upon which believers can confidently build their lives. As David\n'
              'proclaims in Book of Psalms 119:160, the entirety of God\'s Word is\n'
              'truth, and every one of His righteous judgments endures forever. God\'s\n'
              'truth never changes because God Himself never changes.\n'
              'When everything around you is uncertain, God\'s Word remains your\n'
              'unshakable foundation.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🔍',
          heading:
              'Sanctification Is God\'s Ongoing Work',
          body:
              'Jesus prayed, "Sanctify them." Sanctification means to be set apart\n'
              'for God and continually transformed into the likeness of Christ. While\n'
              'salvation happens the moment we place our faith in Jesus,\n'
              'sanctification is a lifelong process in which God gradually shapes our\n'
              'hearts, minds, and character.\n'
              'Many believers become discouraged because they still see areas of\n'
              'weakness within themselves. Yet God never expects instant perfection.\n'
              'He patiently works within His children day by day. As Paul assures\n'
              'believers in Epistle to the Philippians 1:6, He who began a good work\n'
              'will carry it on to completion until the day of Christ Jesus. Every\n'
              'day spent walking with God is another step in His transforming work.\n'
              'God loves you enough to accept you as you are, but He loves you too\n'
              'much to leave you unchanged.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '⚔️',
          heading:
              'Truth Defeats the Lies of the Enemy',
          body:
              'One of Satan\'s greatest weapons is deception. From the Garden of Eden\n'
              'until today, he seeks to distort God\'s truth and replace it with lies\n'
              'that produce fear, confusion, pride, and unbelief. The only effective\n'
              'defense against deception is a heart firmly established in God\'s Word.\n'
              'Jesus Himself demonstrated this during His temptation in the\n'
              'wilderness. Every attack of the enemy was answered with the words, "It\n'
              'is written." As Paul teaches in Epistle to the Ephesians 6:17, the\n'
              'Word of God is the sword of the Spirit, enabling believers to stand\n'
              'against the enemy\'s schemes. Truth exposes deception and gives\n'
              'believers confidence to walk in freedom.\n'
              'A mind filled with God\'s truth cannot easily be conquered by the\n'
              'enemy\'s lies.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🌱',
          heading:
              'God\'s Word Transforms the Heart',
          body:
              'The purpose of Scripture is not merely to increase knowledge but to\n'
              'transform lives. As believers meditate upon God\'s Word, the Holy\n'
              'Spirit uses it to renew their minds, purify their motives, strengthen\n'
              'their faith, and produce Christlike character. True spiritual growth\n'
              'always begins with God\'s truth taking root within the heart.\n'
              'Many people read the Bible simply to gain information, yet God\n'
              'desires transformation. His Word convicts, comforts, instructs,\n'
              'corrects, and encourages His people. As the writer of Epistle to the\n'
              'Hebrews 4:12 explains, God\'s Word is living and powerful, discerning\n'
              'the thoughts and intentions of the heart. The more believers submit to\n'
              'Scripture, the more they become like Christ.\n'
              'The Bible is not merely a book to be read—it is God\'s living voice\n'
              'that transforms those who receive it.\n'
              '---',
        ),
        DevotionalSection(
          icon: '🚶',
          heading:
              'Living by Truth Leads to Freedom',
          body:
              'Jesus prayed that His followers would be sanctified by truth because\n'
              'truth leads to genuine freedom. Freedom is not found in doing whatever\n'
              'we desire but in living according to God\'s design. His truth protects\n'
              'us from sin, guides our decisions, and leads us into abundant life.\n'
              'Every day presents opportunities to choose between the world\'s values\n'
              'and God\'s truth. Those who continually walk in His Word discover\n'
              'increasing peace, wisdom, and spiritual maturity. As Jesus declared in\n'
              'Gospel of John 8:31–32, those who continue in His Word know the truth,\n'
              'and the truth sets them free. God\'s truth liberates the soul from the\n'
              'bondage of sin and fear.\n'
              'Those who build their lives upon God\'s truth will discover the\n'
              'freedom that only Christ can give.\n'
              '---',
        ),
      ],
      finalRevelation:
          'God\'s truth does more than inform your mind—it transforms your heart.\n'
          'As His Word fills your life, your thoughts become renewed, your\n'
          'character becomes more like Christ, and your life becomes set apart\n'
          'for His glory.this ---',
      reflectionQuestions: const [
        'Am I allowing God\'s Word to shape my thinking, or am I being\n'
        'influenced more by the world\'s opinions?',
        'Is there an area of my life where I need God\'s truth to bring\n'
        'transformation?',
        'How can I spend more intentional time meditating on God\'s Word each\n'
        'day?',
      ],
      prayer:
          'Lord,\n'
          'Thank You for the gift of Your holy and unchanging Word. Thank You\n'
          'that Your truth is perfect, trustworthy, and powerful enough to\n'
          'transform my life. I praise You because Your Word never fails and\n'
          'always leads me in the path of righteousness.\n'
          'Sanctify my heart through Your truth. Remove every lie, wrong belief,\n'
          'and sinful attitude that keeps me from becoming more like Jesus. Renew\n'
          'my mind each day through the power of Your Word, and help me to love\n'
          'Your truth above every voice this world offers.\n'
          'Teach me to meditate on Scripture, obey it faithfully, and allow it\n'
          'to shape every decision I make. Fill me with wisdom, discernment, and\n'
          'spiritual understanding so that I may walk in freedom and reflect the\n'
          'character of Christ.\n'
          'May Your truth become the foundation of my life, the light that\n'
          'guides my path, and the transforming power that continually makes me\n'
          'more like my Savior.\n'
          'Amen. 🙏🌿',
      createdAt: DateTime(2024, 3, 28),
    ),
  ];
